    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Roofed porch or lean-to pent roofs that extend from a building, especially of a temple hall or of a "tahōtō." They usually surround the main part of the building and were used as a method to increase depth. This architectural element was widely used in Zen-style architecture introduced to Japan in the late 12th century.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
